<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Up 1.3 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Factory orders increased
by a strong 1.3 percent in August resulting mainly from a surge in
demand for electronic components, U.S. Commerce Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
The department reported that U.S. factory orders jumped to a
seasonally adjusted 335.4 billion dollars in the month after gains
of 0.5 percent in July and 1.7 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The August rise in factory orders was more than accounted for
by a 76.9 percent surge in orders for electronic components such
as semiconductors and circuit boards.
</P>
<P>
Factory orders on durable goods -- items expected to last for
more than three years -- increased by 2.7 percent but orders for
nondurable goods declined by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of factory goods, a measure of current production,
fell by 0.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted 330.4 billion dollars
in August. It was the first drop since May and was attributed to
the United Parcel Service strike.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the shipments decline, unfilled orders rose 1
percent to a seasonally adjusted 527.2 billion dollars. Factory
inventories rose by 0.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted 448.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
The report fits with U.S. analysts' belief that the economic
growth is stabilizing after increasing at a 4.1 percent annual
rate in the first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
