<HEADLINE> Britain to Demand Relaxation of EU Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
unveiled a new initiative on exporting cattles with convincing
records in an effort to ease the European Union's (EU) world-wide
ban on exports of British beef products.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham told reporters
early today that the London government would ask Britain's EU
partners later today to examine detailed plans that would ask for
the export of beef from animals born after August 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
"We have to convince our European partners, there's no other
way. We can't act independently in these matters," Cunningham
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal known as a "date-based scheme", meat from
cattles born after the specified date and from which some risky
parts has been removed could be exported to other European
countries again.
</P>
<P>
Early last month the EU's scientific veterinary committee
indicated that exports of British beef could resume if there was a
computerized system to trace animals and make sure none had come
into contact with mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The scheme may only effectively help Northern Ireland at the
moment in resuming beef exports, since it is the only British
region where such a computerized tracking system is in operation.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a global ban on British beef exports in March
1996 after the British government admitted possible links between
mad cow disease and its human equivalent Creutzdfeldt Jacob
Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
