<HEADLINE> 192 Crime Syndicates In S. Africa, Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 192 organized
crime syndicates were known to be operating in South Africa,
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said today.
</P>
<P>
He told the National Assembly that 1,903 "primary suspects"
connected with the syndicates had been pinpointed by May this
year, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that 92 hostage-taking incidents occurred in the
country between July 1, 1996 and August 29, 1997 with 198
hostages involved.
</P>
<P>
Seven people were killed and 13 injured in the incidents.
</P>
<P>
About one third of these incidents, or 29, related to domestic
or financial problems and unfaithfulness, seven to robbery, three
to threatened family murders, four to vehicle hijack attempts and
four to jails.
</P>
<P>
It seems that crime has become an epidemic in South Africa.
Severe crimes such as murder, rape and robbery were believed to
have withheld the inflow of foreign investors and tourists, two
things much needed by South Africa to rejuvenate its economy.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi also disclosed that 103 policemen had committed
suicide this year by September 10. In the whole year of 1996, the
figure was 160.
</P>
<P>
In the 12-month period to August 31 this year, there were 173
deaths in police custody, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
