<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. College Students Spend $5.5 Billion on Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. college students spend
5.5 billion U.S. dollars on alcohol each year, more than on books,
soda, coffee, juice and milk combined, said the Christian Science
Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1995 nationwide survey of college students by
the Harvard University, 44 percent admitted to drinking in binges
(meaning that men drink five or more drinks at a setting, and
women drink four or more). Members of fraternities and sororities
are among the most likely to binge, at 86 percent and 80 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Campus alcohol-abuse has brought a number of problems and the
issue is becoming urgent. Binge drinking has become a sad fact of
life on most college campuses. This year alone, three students
have died from injuries sustained while drunk. The latest case was
the death of a Massachusetts Institute of Technology student from
overdrinking this week.
</P>
<P>
The report said that many colleges sell alcohol at sports
events and some even sell bear ad T-shirts. Experts called for new
rules to curb the abuse.
</P>
<P>
Some campuses are experimenting aggressive new ways. The State
University of New York in Albany has worked out an agreement with
off-campus tavern owners to stop happy hours and avoid selling to
minors; Ohio State University in Columbus suspended a dozen
students after a drunken post-football-game riot in 1996; and the
University of Rhode Island at Kingston has banned alcohol at all
campus activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
