<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Depreciating Zimbabwe Dollar to Push up Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce (ZNCC) said today the dramatic fall in the Zimbabwe
Dollar this week is likely to result in higher prices for
imported goods currently being stocked for the Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
Edmore Tobaiwa, vice-chairman of the ZNCC national standing
committee on economics, trade and taxation, said the slide in the
local currency which began about four weeks ago is putting
pressure on commercial enterprises stocking up for the festive
season.
</P>
<P>
"To that end it will result in high prices for the highly
traded imported goods during that season," Tobaiwa noted.
</P>
<P>
The local currency unit, which exporters say was overvalued by
five percent, plunged to the 13:1 levels against the U.S. Dollar
on Monday before the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe intervened to bring
it back to 12.7 Zimbabwe Dollars to the U.S. Dollar on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks the unit had been trading at just under
12 Zimbabwe Dollars to the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Speculation had been rife that the local currency unit would
fall before the end of year, resulting in exporters keeping their
revenue in hard currency, and shortage of foreign currency on the
local market which increased pressure on the local Dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
