<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Trains Businessmen for Small Scale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 600 aspiring business
people from three sub-Saharan countries were trained on how to
start and run businesses under a program of the International
Labor Organization (ILO), an ILO official said today.
</P>
<P>
At the one-day Micro and Small Scale Enterprise Promotion
Network (MISSEP) in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest city, ILO
official Chakanetsa Rukobo said, about 400 of the 600 people
trained in Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe under the Start Your
Business Program (SYB) were from Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Between 18 and 20 percent of the people actually started
businesses after being trained under the program," Rukobo said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that small-to-medium scale enterprises
still face a number of problems such as access to finance,
collateral, high interest rates and the disbursement rate of the
loans.
</P>
<P>
SYB is a business start-up training program which enables
entrepreneurs to evaluate the viability of their business ideas,
and provides them with the skills to start their own business.
</P>
<P>
Rukobo said ILO had a mandate for employment creation and
encouraging people to start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
The ILO was also implementing another program named "Improve
Your Business (IYB)" for people who would have managed to set up
businesses but need further training to improve them.
</P>
<P>
This program was being implemented in 15 African countries
including Angola, Botswana, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Lesotho,
Tanzania, Uganda, Malawi and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Up to the end of 1995, 26,000 entrepreneurs in the 15
countries had been trained, and between 80 and 90 showed signs of
improving their businesses," Rukobo noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
