<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Privatize Loss-Making Parastatals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today reaffirmed the government's determination to
privatize loss-making parastatal enterprises which he blamed for
the country's huge budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Officially commissioning Forestry Commission's Chimanimani
Sawmill in east Zimbabwe, Mugabe said the government would not
backtrack on privatizing loss-making parastatals.
</P>
<P>
The government policy was that all public enterprises
producing marketable services should cease to be a burden on the
fiscal, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Instead, they must be made to be self-financing and
self-sustaining and, in due course, must in fact be a source of
revenue for the government through taxing and payment of
dividends," the president told thousands of people who witnessed
the commissioning.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said privatization would enable the government to focus
on its core business of running the politics of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Plans are at an advanced stage to commercialize and later on
privatize the remainder of the targeted loss-making parastatals,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Chimanimani Sawmill is the country's largest sawmill with a
processing capacity of 125,000 cubic meters of round logs and
55,000 cubic meters of sawn timber a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
