<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Sets for Talks in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- President Glafcos Clerides
departed today for New York for talks on the Cyprus problem and
especially his proposal for demilitarizing the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before his departure, President Clerides said the
objective of his meetings during his tour will be "to promote a
solution to the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he will focus especially on the
demilitarization of the island, Turkish threats against Cyprus and
other relevant issues.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides will address the U.N. General Assembly and
is expected to have meetings with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and U.S. Presidential envoy on Cyprus Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
After his stay in New York, he will fly on to Washington, and
then France, Britain and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Clerides' proposal for demilitarization, put forward in 1993,
promises disbanding the Cypriot National Guard and handing over
its weapons and equipment to the U.N. Peace-keeping Force in
Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
In return, the proposal calls for withdrawal of the Turkish
troops from the island and disbanding of the Turkish Cypriot armed
forces. Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot side have rejected the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000-strong troops in the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern part of the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
