<HEADLINE> Sergeyev on Russian-NATO Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 2 (Xinhua) -- There are no reasons today for
splitting up Europe's strategic space into counterpoised poles,
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said here today after
returning from Maastricht, where an informal meeting of the NATO
defense ministers was held on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass quoted Sergeyev as saying that constructive
cooperation between Russia and the North Atlantic Alliance must be
the foundation for stability and security in future Europe.
</P>
<P>
On the problem of NATO's eastward enlargement, Sergeyev said
through the Founding Act was signed in Paris, Russia still regards
the NATO enlargement plans as a factor that does not contribute to
the stabilization of the military-political situation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia, the minister said, comes out for the transformation of
the North Atlantic Alliance from a military-political bloc into a
political organization.
</P>
<P>
The Founding Act "stipulates for the first time nineteen areas
of cooperation between Russia and NATO, beginning from joint
actions in case of critical situations and ending with measures to
combat terrorism and drug trafficking", Sergeyev said, so it
offers additional military-political chances to promote stability
and is an effective instrument for jointly countering military
threats.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the 16 NATO countries are nowable to hold
consultations on an equal footing within the Joint Permanent
Council on a broad range of problems, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev also stressed that he preferred to see the Council as
a body that will "ensure a higher level of trust in the process of
cooperation between Russia and NATO in order to enhance each other's
security and the security of all the countries in the
Euro-Atlantic Region." 
</P>
</TEXT>
