<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Proposes to Ensure Primary Agricultural Product Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has put forward a proposal
for people throughout the Single Market to seek compensation for
damages caused by defective primary agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was put forward by the Commission on the
initiative of Single Market Commissioner Mario Monti, which takes
the form of a proposal to include primary agricultural products in
the scope of the EU's existing product liability directive, it was
learned here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The directive on product liability requires the producer or
importer to pay compensation if there is a link found between the
damage and the defect, without a person having to prove negligence
on the part of the producer or importer.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament's report on bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE) has specifically requested the Commission to
present such a proposal.
</P>
<P>
"This proposal responds to people's legitimate consumer
concerns about the safety of primary agricultural products within
the Single Market," said Mr. Monti.
</P>
<P>
Following recent anxiety over BSE, the commissioner said, the
proposal will provide an additional incentive for producers and
importers of primary agricultural products in the EU to ensure
that product safety receives top priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
