<HEADLINE> New UK Proposal to Lift European Ban on Beef Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, October 2 (Xinhua) - A proposal aimed at
restarting British beef exports has been put forward by
Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would lift the export ban for all cattle born
after 1 August 1996 and clear the way for British beef farmers to
re-enter world markets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Conference, Cunningham said: "This is a
positive step in our new approach to lifting the beef export ban."
</P>
<P>
The plan has now been formally submitted to the European
Commission, according to the Minister.
</P>
<P>
At the European Head of Government meeting in Florence on 21
June 1996 agreement was reached on a framework for the progressive
removal of the ban on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
The "Florence Framework" required Britain to meet a number of
pre-conditions reflecting its agreed plan for the eradication of
BSE.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham said: "The main way in which cattle have been
infected with BSE is through feed. Since August 1996 the UK has
enforced very strict controls to make sure that feed does not
contain meat and bone meal."
</P>
<P>
The Minister today also proposed the compulsory slaughter of
all offspring from BSE infected cows born on or after 1 August
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Date Based Export Scheme proposed by the British
government, together with the cull of animals potentially at risk
of BSE through maternal transmission, sets strict rules under
which beef exports could resume.
</P>
<P>
However, Cunningham said that "Lifting the export ban is a
priority. The way to do this is not by shouting and being
unrealistic. It must be by co-operation and constructive
dialogue."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
