<HEADLINE> Qatar to Host Planned Mideast, North Africa Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 2 (Xinhua) - Qatar has decided to go
ahead with the plan to host the Fourth Economic Summit for the
Middle East and North Africa next November despite some
controversies among Arab nations, the country's foreign minister
said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister, Sheikh Hamad Jassim bin Jabr al-Thani, made the
announcement in a speech at the general debate of the United
Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab nations thought that conference, planned to be held
in Doha, should be canceled because of the current Israeli policy
"that did not respect the undertaking and agreements, flouting the
international legality and trying to marginalize the role of the
United Nations."
</P>
<P>
While understanding that view, Qatar respected its
international commitments and believed that no states should have
the power to veto the peace process, Hamad noted.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we decided to host the conference during the
announced period. If the conference does not prove to be
successful and does not achieve the desired results, only the
government of Israel will be responsible for that," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qatar had committed itself at the Economic Summit of Amman in
1995 to hosting the fourth summit. 
</P>
