<HEADLINE> Most of Zambian Employees in Informal Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
worried with the fact that most of employees are working in
informal sector.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Social Security Minister Peter Machungwa told
parliament here today that in 1996, there were 2,398,000 people
employed in the informal sector and only 468,000 were in the
formal sector.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the downward trend of the formal sector
is merely a short run phenomenon associated with the
liberalization policies the government has embarked upon.
</P>
<P>
The trend is expected to be reversed in the long term when the
country's economy stabilizes as employment creation accelerates,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa also told the house that so far 80 Zambian
professionals who went for greener pastures abroad have been
attracted back into the country following positive measures
including improved salaries.
</P>
<P>
He singled out the equal work, equal pay principle being
encouraged by the government as the main incentive that is
attracting professionals from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of funds, the government does not have the data
bank on Zambian professionals to ascertain how many such
professionals have left to work in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The system will be put in place by the next year as funds
become available, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
