<HEADLINE> E. Europe Should Have Seat on Security Council, Belarus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Belarus is in favor of
Eastern Europe having one seat on the U.N. Security Council as
part of the reform of the international organization.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the General Assembly here today, Ivan Antonovich,
Belarus Foreign Minister, said that the Republic of Belarus is
convinced that allocation of one more non-permanent seat on the
Security Council to the Eastern European regional group is in full
compliance with the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The members from the region in the United Nations have more
than doubled over recent years. They should have a representative
in the Security Council, in line with the principle of equitable
geographical representation, according to the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He quoted the president of Belarus as saying that the United
Nations' reforms should be directed at strengthening the
organization's potentials in peacekeeping, humanitarian and
information services.
</P>
<P>
The functional efficiency of the U.N. system also includes
effective distribution of resources, streamlining administrative and
organizational structures, structural and budgetary changes at the
Secretariat, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating Belarus' opposition to the expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), he said his country favored
NATO's transformation into a universal European organization for
peace and security. Belarus had entered into negotiations with
NATO for its participation in the "Partnership for Peace".
</P>
</TEXT>
