<HEADLINE> Trade of Oman, Japan Rises Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Trade volume between Oman and
Japan rose to 1.23 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of
this year from 1.21 billion dollars a year earlier, the Omani News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports to Oman reached 344.1 million dollars in the
period, an increase of 8.9 percent, while its imports amounted to
893 million dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Japan mainly exported machinery, electronic equipment and
trucks to Oman, and imported crude oil.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, Japan imported 38.6 million
barrels of crude oil from Oman, 6.2 million barrels less than in
the same period of this year.
</P>
<P>
However, due to a 16.1 percent increase in crude price which
reached 18.81 dollars a barrel, Japan registered a nominal
increase of 0.1 percent in oil import from Oman, amounting to
843.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Oman is the eighth largest oil supplier to Japan, providing
about 4.7 percent of Japan's overall oil imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
