<HEADLINE> Violent Crime by Teens Dropped in 1996 in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno announced Thursday arrests for juvenile violent crime plunged
9.2 percent in 1996, the second drop after a juvenile crime wave
of seven years.
</P>
<P>
A 2.9 percent drop in juvenile violence arrests in 1995 was the
first such reduction in seven years, and Reno said, "This drop I
think is for real now."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, for every 100,000 youths aged 10 to 17, there were
464.7 arrests for violent crimes, down from 511.9 in 1995 and
527.4 in the peak year of 1994, according FBI figures.
</P>
<P>
FBI Uniform Crime Report figures for all categories are
scheduled to be released this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Reno attributed the drop to a number of factors, including
provisions in the 1994 Crime Act.
</P>
<P>
She also credits "young people working to keep their friends
and their peers from turning to violence."
</P>
<P>
In responding to questions about several murders by juveniles
around the country in the last few days, Reno said juvenile
violence is "still too high" after record increases from 1986 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
She also promoted Clinton's proposed juvenile crime bill now in
Congress, which contains after-school activities to keep teenagers
away from crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
