<HEADLINE> US Official Acknowledges Criticisms of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A key U.S. official has
acknowledged international criticisms of U.S. sanctions policies
and said Washington needs to make them "part of a coherent
strategy" including seeking multilateral support.
</P>
<P>
"We... find value in many of them (international criticisms)
and will factor them into our future work," Undersecretary of
State Stuart Eizenstat said in a speech last Friday to the Global
Business Forum, which was made available today.
</P>
<P>
The United States should meet the challenge, he said, "to find
a way to improve the way we make sanctions decisions, to ensure
that sanctions are part of a coherent strategy, to accurately
measure the costs and effects of sanctions measures, to seek
multilateral support where possible and to improve coordination
between the administration and Congress."
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat agreed that sanctions hurt the U.S. economy --
costing more than 19 billion dollars in 1995 in lost export sales
and 250,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The figures he cited come from a report by the President's
Export Council, which also said sanctions undermine confidence in
the reliability of U.S. suppliers, provide a competitive advantage
for foreign firms and impose costs on third parties and innocent
civilians in countries subject to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Reuters, which got a copy of Eizenstat's speech from the State
Department at its request, said the undersecretary's views are
important because he is a key U.S. official involved with U.S.
sanctions disputes with Europe and other countries.
</P>
<P>
This includes the row over the French oil giant Total SA and
its partners, Russian Gazprom and Malaysian Petronas who announced
on September 28 a 2 billion dollar contract with Iran to develop
Iran's South Pars natural gas field.
</P>
<P>
The United States threatened Monday to impose the 1996
Iran-Libya Sanctions Act on Total and its Russian and Malaysian
partners but was greeted with scoff from the French government,
which proclaimed Washington has no right to impose its law beyond
its border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
