<HEADLINE> NASA Plans New Communication With Mars Pathfinder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Aeronautics
and Space Administration (NASA) is planning to find ways to
communicate with Pathfinder on the Mars that has now outlived its
original minimum design life by nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
NASA scientists said today that it's possible its battery is
dead and solar energy will have to be used in the future.
</P>
<P>
After three days of problems communicating with the spacecraft,
controllers were able to re-establish enough contact with
Pathfinder through an auxiliary transmitter to determine it's
still operational.
</P>
<P>
Another similar signal was received today, but again no data
was transmitted, Project Manager Brian Muirhead said.
</P>
<P>
Muirhead is certain that the lander's battery had finally died,
which would mean that using the spacecraft would require devising
new ways to control Pathfinder during periods when its solar
panels are generating enough power.
</P>
<P>
Pathfinder reached the red planet on July 4. The lander was
designed to operate a minimum of 30 days, while its little mobile
rover, Sojourner, was designed to operate just seven days.
However, both are still operating.
</P>
<P>
They have sent back clear images of the martian landscape,
sunrises and frozen ice clouds, and relayed chemical analyses of
rocks on the Mars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says He Won't Pressure Reno on Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today he won't pressure Attorney General Janet Reno in any
way as she weighs whether to open a further probe of White House
fund-raising phone calls.
</P>
<P>
Clinton hinted that if Reno does order a 90-day preliminary
investigation of him or Vice President Al Gore, the next step in
the process toward appointment of an independent counsel, it might
be helpful.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Rose Garden with Gore at his side, Clinton
said, "This is a legal question and it should be done based on an
independent legal review, with no pressure from the outside from
me or from anyone else. And that's the way I intend to keep it, at
least on my part."
</P>
<P>
Reno should decide by Friday whether to begin such an
investigation of Gore's fund-raising calls in the 1996 elections.
She has until October 15 to decide in Clinton's case.
</P>
<P>
Reno is considering whether the 1883 federal law, never tested
in court, prevents Clinton or Gore from soliciting funds by
telephone on federal property. Gore has admitted making such calls
from his office but insists he never meant to raise so-called hard
money that goes directly to campaigns. The Democratic National
Committee did channel some of Gore's proceeds into hard money
accounts, which is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he is unsure he made fund-raising calls from his
office, despite memos urging him to do so.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reno is declining to answer questions on whether she
would order the preliminary investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
