<HEADLINE> Palestinians Cautiously Welcome Israeli Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian permanent
representative to the Arab League Mohamed Sobeih has expressed
hope that the release of Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder of Hamas,
would lead to the release of all the Palestinian detainees in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Middle East News Agency
(MENA) today, Sobeih said that Israel must set free all the
Palestinians it detained, which was an indivisible part of the
peace process between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Israel on Wednesday released Hamas' spiritual leader Yassin,
who was then flown to Amman aboard a Jordanian airplane.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, an eloquent preacher, founded Hamas in December 1987
following the outbreak of the Palestinian uprising (Intifada) in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. He was arrested by the Israeli
authorities and sentenced to life imprisonment in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih called on the United States to intensify its efforts to
rescue the peace process, and urged Israel to immediately cease
its construction of Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel's continued siege of the Palestinian
self-ruled areas violated the principles of peace and the signed
agreements, and would undermine the atmosphere of confidence
required to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qodra
expressed cautious welcome to the release of Yassin by Israel,
saying that this move might be aimed to cater for world opinion.
</P>
<P>
He said that Yassin should be allowed to return to Gaza as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
Arab diplomatic sources here said that Israel's release of
Yassin was mainly aimed at demonstrating a positive sign of
goodwill to the Arab world to encourage them to attend the Middle
East and North Africa Economic Summit, due to be held in November
in Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that by releasing Yassin and handing
him over to Jordan, Israel was to contain the political crisis
which erupted between the two countries following the attempted
murder of Khalid Mashiel, leader of Hamas' political bureau, by
suspected Israeli Mossad agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
