<HEADLINE> Lijiang Recovers from Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Lijiang prefecture in southwest
China's Yunnan province has rehabilitated from a strong earthquake
on February 2 last year which led to a toll of 300 and 16,000
injuries.
</P>
<P>
The quake measured 7.0 on the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
So far, the prefecture's industrial and agricultural output has
reached the pre-quake level, local officials said. In the first
half of this year, its industrial output value increased by 12.7
percent to reach 384 million yuan (46.3 million US dollars) over
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 64,000 families, or 97 percent of the total affected by
the quake, have had their houses rebuilt or repaired in ther
past-odd year. Moreover, the local prefectural government has
earmarked 100 million yuan (12.05 million US dollars) to rebuild
400 schools and reinforced another 236, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals, theaters and stadiums have also been renovated. And
a new street has been built in downtown Lijiang.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has also revived. In the first half of this year, some
920,000 tourists, or the total number the region received in the
whole 1996, visited Lijiang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government plans to apply for the inclusion of
Lijiang on the UNESCO's world culture heritage list for its unique
folk culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
