<HEADLINE> France, Italy Present Joint Initiative on Jobs in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- France and Italy today presented a
joint initiative on reducing working week time to help create jobs
in Europe, said official of the two countries attending the annual
Franco-Italian summit held in Chambery, southeast France.
</P>
<P>
This initiative, launched by French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin and his Italian counterpart Romano Prodi, will be presented
at the European Union (EU) extraordinary conference on jobs to be
held on November 20-21 in Luxembourg, said officials.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac also described the initiative
"excellent" and "well-balanced." He pointed out that he
himself has been fighting for two years to make Europe a world
example in the social field.
</P>
<P>
Paris and Rome held that a reduction of weekly working time is
helpful for creating jobs and increasing the flexibility of job
market.
</P>
<P>
France and Italy did not propose any legally fixed weekly
working time, and instead suggested a better concertation between
employers and employees to make social projects with financial
support from the governments.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government of France has just presented a law on
reducing weekly working time to 35 hours in order to help the
country's youth get jobs and fight unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of France and Italy also reached "total
convergence of views" on European economic and monetary union, EU
enlargement, EU institutional reform and major international
issues.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed confidence over their countries' capability
to join the European single currency euro on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac suggested that France and Italy cooperate in
aeronautics and air transport industries, and two countries agreed
to construct a trans-Alpes TGV bullet train railway between the
French city Lyon and Italian city Turin for transporting
passengers and commodities, despite opposition from ecologists.
</P>
</TEXT>
