<HEADLINE> Beijing Well-lighted with Colorful Bulbs During National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Chang'an Avenue, a five-km main
avenue crossing Tiananmen Square in the heart of Beijing, is awash
in the high-powered glow of thousands upon thousands of colorful
bulbs, lanterns and neon lights switched on for the three-day
National Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
"It is literally as bright as the Champs Elysees in Paris,"
said Yuan Zengyi, director of the Street Light Department of the
municipality's electricity supply bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 4,000 streetlights on the Second Ring
Road, which are normally turned off to conserve electricity, are
on for the occasion, and blazing sodium-filament lights have
replaced ordinary ones along main roads to give passersby an even
brighter view.
</P>
<P>
Some 80,000 streetlights, including those on the Third Ring
Road, on expressways heading to cities and areas outside Beijing
and on the side roads, have all been re-wired to illuminate the
capital during the festival.
</P>
<P>
The Tiananmen Square, a major symbol of Beijing, is dripping
with lanterns, neon and floodlights.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, approximately 300 special evening lights along the
Chang'an Avenue are all on, and colorful bulbs outline the large
buildings near the square.
</P>
<P>
And there is more to come, Yuan said. Plans are underway to
make Beijing sparkle even brighter at nighttime, and not only
during holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
