<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Holds Steady in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate in
September was unchanged at 4.9 percent, near the lowest level in
24 years, the U.S. Labor Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate last month matched the August rate and
was just a little above the 4.8 percent rate in July and May, the
lowest since 1973.
</P>
<P>
The department said employers added 215,000 jobs to their
payroll in September, up from a paltry 40,000 in August, the
fewest in 11 months.
</P>
<P>
The service sectors in the United States showed the biggest
increase in job creation with new employment of 229,000 in
September. Computer, engineering and management services also
posted healthy gains.
</P>
<P>
The employment in the mining sector, which has been falling for
a long time, rose by 3,000 jobs, most of which were in the oil and
gas industry.
</P>
<P>
However, manufacturers cut 16,000 jobs, with declines
concentrated in auto plants and clothing factories.
</P>
<P>
Among demographic groups, the U.S. unemployment in September
was 4.1 percent for adult men and 4.4 percent for adult women,
both unchanged. The jobless rate for teenagers was up to 16.7
percent from 16.4 percent. The rates were 4.3 percent for the
whites and 9.6 percent for the blacks, up respectively from 4.2
percent and 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, average hourly earnings of non-supervisory workers
in the country jumped by 4 cents last month to a seasonally
adjusted 12.34 dollars following a 6-cent increase in August. The
average work week declined from 34.6 hours in August to 34.5 hours
in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
