<HEADLINE> Russia Hopes NATO Turns Into a Peace-Keeping Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said that his country hopes the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) turns into a political or peace-keeping organization, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a joint interview with Russian and French TV stations,
Yeltsin spoke warmly of the development of bilateral relations
since the signing of the Russia-NATO Founding Act in Paris on May
27.
</P>
<P>
The president also described the first meeting of the
Russian-NATO Permanent Joint Council on September 26 as "very
substantial."
</P>
<P>
"This," Yeltsin said, "provides reasons to hope that the
development will move in a constructive direction."
</P>
<P>
However, Russia would like to see NATO transformed into a
political or at least a peace-keeping organization rather than
remaining as a military alliance, the president added.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that if NATO decided to do anything against the
Founding Act, Russia would certainly respond.
</P>
<P>
As for existing borders in Europe, the Russian president said
there would be no new divisions or re-drawings; World War II had
yielded excellent results. 
</P>
