<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Committed to Equipping Air Force: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government views
the need to re-equip the air force with modern equipment as a
matter of urgency, and is also committed to improving conditions
of service for pilots, President Robert Mugabe said today.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is Commander-in-Chief, said he was concerned with
the logistical problems faced by the air force in areas such as
servicing old equipment and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
New equipment would enhance protection of Zimbabwe's airspace
and secure the country's defense capability and preparedness, he
said in a speech read on his behalf by Vice-President Simon
Muzenda.
</P>
<P>
Turning to conditions of service during a graduation ceremony
for 13 officer cadets at Thornhill air basel in central Zimbabwe,
Mugabe said, ''the government is fully aware of the unfavorable
conditions of service of pilots in the air force of Zimbabwe, and
will strive to correct the situation when the economy improves
and more resources are made available.''
</P>
<P>
Commending the air force for its pragmatic endeavor to achieve
self-sufficiency in manpower training, Mugabe said the Defense
Ministry had embarked on a procurement program to re-equip the
defense forces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cadet offices Basil Govindan was voted best
recruit, while women cadets Sheila Musende and Sithandekile Dube
were among the 13 graduates.
</P>
<P>
This brings to three the number of women pilots trained at the
air basekile.
</P>
<P>
''It is important to note that this positive development
fulfills our stated national policy objective of gender
equality,'' said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The two-year course covered military officership, etiquette
and aviation-related subjects such as aero-dynamics,
aero-engines, instrument meteorology, aerospace and aircraft
electronics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
