<HEADLINE> Chinese, Thai Military Leaders Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- General Chi Haotian,
vice-chairman of the Chinese Central Military Commission, met with
with General Mongkon Ampornpisit, supreme commander of the Armed
Forces of Thailand, here today.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also state councillor and minister of national defense,
while extending his welcome, said he believed that Mongkon's
ongoing visit will surely serve to expand the existing friendly
ties between the two countries and their armies, and help increase
the unity and cooperation between the two armies.
</P>
<P>
The frequent exchange of visits between leaders of the two
armies has laid a good basis for developing bilateral friendly
ties in various fields, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the future, Chi said, both armies should reinforce exchanges
at all ranks and levels, and in all fields in a bid to pass on the
family-like friendship from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said that as for international and regional
affairs, the people of the two nations have sympathized with,
supported and helped each other, and made positive contributions
to safeguarding regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The two countries share identical or similar views on many
major international and regional issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chi briefed the Thai supreme commander on China's economic
development, army building and the recent 15th National Congress
of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Supreme Commander Mongkon expressed the
hope to further promote the friendly cooperative relations between
the two countries and the two armies.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Kui Fulin, deputy chief of General Staff of
the Chinese People Liberation Army (PLA), was among those present
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Supreme Commander is here as guest of General Fu
Quanyou, chief of the PLA General Staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
