<HEADLINE> China to Further Cooperate with Other Countries on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- China has made remarkable
progress in environmental protection over the past few years, and
will continue to cooperate with other counties so as to further
improve its environment.
</P>
<P>
Chinese State Councilor Song Jian made the remarks here today
while addressing the opening ceremony of the First Meeting of
the Second Phase of China Council for International Cooperation on
Environment and Develoment.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has made new achievements in environmental
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese National People's Congress (NPC) promulgated the
"Law on the Prevention and Control of Noise Pollution of the
People's Republic of China" in October 1996, marking the basic
completion of the legal system on the prevention and control of
water, gas, noise and solid waste pollution, said Song, who is
also chairman of the State Council's Environmental Protection
Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, China still faces serious challenges for its
environmental protection, he noted, and the goal set by the
Chinese government for the year 2000 is to curb the trend of
environmental pollution and ecological degradation with
improvement of environmental quality in some cities and regions
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Bureau of Environment
Protection of China, briefed the participants on the country's
achievements in biodiversity protection, pollution control,
cleaner production, and the implementation of certifications by
the international environmental system.
</P>
<P>
Xie said China has established 800 nature reserves throughout
the country with a total area of 71.85 million
hectares. They account for about 7.2 percent of the Chinese
territories, higher than the world average. Twelve nature reserves
have joined the International Man and Biosphere Reserve Network.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1992, the China Council for International
Cooperation on Environment and Development is composed of senior
officials and scholars from at home and abroad, and intended
to explore new ways of international cooperation in environmental,
economic and social development, sciences and technology, in line with
China's national characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting is expected to focus on environment and
trade, environmental protection and economic plans, sustained
agricultural advancement as well as the implementation of
international environment conventions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
