<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Technician Buys Enterprise Shares With Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Ph.D. Shen Hao recently pledged
his patented technology for a 17 percent share of a newly-founded
paint company in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
His share is valued at 5.1 million yuan (614,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
A local government official said that Shen became the first
student to return to China and use intellectual property rights in
the form of patented technology to buy shares in a state-owned
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the development to Jiang Zemin's
Sept. 12 report to the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) encouraging the realization of diversified
forms of public ownership.
</P>
<P>
The two major shareholders in thee high-tech company are
state-owned enterprises in the city.
</P>
<P>
Shen's share-holding position calls for him to provide the
company with patented technology, development programs, technical
upgrades and technological services.
</P>
<P>
Shen, who has since been elected the company's general manager,
graduated from the Chemistry Dept. at the Chinese University of
Science and Technology, and later earned a Ph.D. in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
Shen, who also worked for research institutes in both Britain
and Norway, has been granted some 30-odd state patents for high
quality specialty paint products which can be used by the
automobile, container, marine engineering and light industrial
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Wang Youming, an official with the Shenzhen Science and
Technology Bureau, said that the city has encouraged the
development of high-tech enterprises by allowing scientists and
technicians purchase to share with patented technology.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the city has listed 20 enterprises as
the units for the reform project on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has been a pioneer in China's implementation of
opening-up and moderization over the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
