<HEADLINE> Shareholding System Enters Art Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The popular shareholding system
has made its way into the arts sector in China's biggest commercial
center Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
A small performance art troupe has announced that it will adopt
the system to get more funding, and in turn stage better shows, in
keeping with the market economy.
</P>
<P>
"The system will turn the actors and actresses into the real
masters of the troupe. Therefore, they will have a sincere
interest in everything involving the troupe," said Zhang Dongping,
head of the Changning Hu Opera Troupe.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Opera, or Hu Opera as locals call it, is a typical
kind of local operas performed in Shanghai dialect.
</P>
<P>
According to the new rule, for every new play, the troupe will
buy 52 shares of the total investment, and individual performers
and workers will buy the rest.
</P>
<P>
The profits will be divided among them according to the
box-office revenue, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
At present, China boasts 57,000 theatrical troupes, mostly
government-run. Like state-owned industrial enterprises, many of
them are also losing money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
