<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striding toward Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shanghai
municipality, the country's biggest economic and financial center,
is picking up its pace to become a comprehensive modern metropolis
as new China enters its 48th year.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 billion yuan (14.46 billion US dollars) has been
injected into the city construction projects during the past half
decade, five times the amount spent in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, the city's airport, which has air routes
connecting 97 interior and overseas cities, transported more than
six million passengers, exceeding the number for all of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The import and export volumes of the city's harbor totaled 53
billion US dollars in 1996, 1.6 times more than five years
before. The trade volume of post and telecommunications reached
eight billion yuan (964,000 US dollars) last year, six times the
figure of 1992.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a multiple industrial system, composed of
automobile, metallurgical, telecommunications and bio-engineering
industries and the rich service sector has been formed in this
east China's port city, which used to be solely a textile center.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that the per-capita output value of Shanghai
will surpass 3,000 US dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city has also made notable progress in
urbanization of its suburban areas. Large groups of factories
moved from downtown area to the outskirtan areas, making room for
huge theaters, stadiums and recreational centers to be built to
bring in more tourists from both at home and overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
