<HEADLINE> Chinese Archeologists Find 5,000-year-old Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered samples of carbonized rice believed to be planted by
people living some 5,000 to 6,000 years ago in the Yellow River
valley.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that ancient rice has been found along
the Yellow River, the cradle of Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
In ancient times, Chinese people usually planted rice along the
Yangtze River and in southeastern coastal areas, but produced
grain along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The find is thus an important contribution to the study of the
origin and development of Chinese agriculture, the archeologists
said.
</P>
<P>
The rice was discovered in Quanhu village of northwest China's
Shaanxi province, where the archeologists have also found cave
dwellings built by ancient residents, who are believed to have
planted the rice.
</P>
<P>
The round-shaped houses were built half underground, arranged
in parallel lines that spread as far as 50 meters. Pottery jars
and other relics have been unearthed at the site.
</P>
<P>
The site belongs to the famous Yangshao Culture, a culture of
the Neolithic period with a well-developed agricultural system
about 6,000 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
