<HEADLINE> Chongqing of China Lists Tourism as Pillar Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, China's newly-founded
municipality administrated directly by the central government, has
listed tourism as a pillar industry to promote its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to rely on the machine-building,
metallurgical, and chemical industries in economic development,
Chongqing, a major industrial base in southwest China, plans to
stress the development of tourism to reduce environmental
pollution and boost economic growth in its poor rural areas,
municipal officials said.
</P>
<P>
With numerous historical sites and natural scenery such as the
Three Gorges of the Yangtze River and the Stone Carvings at Dazu,
Chongqing has already become a leading tourist attraction in the
country, ranking after Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin in
terms of the domestic tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the municipality received
114,000 overseas tourists, a year-on-year increase of 38 percent,
and the tourism earnings topped 37 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Miner Three Gorges alone received 670,000 Chinese tourists
from January to June, a rise of 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a new economic development plan, Chongqing will
raise the proportion of tourism in its GNP value to eight to ten
percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
"We'll make great efforts in improving the service of tourism,
enhancing the management, intensifying construction of tourism
facilities, and absorbing overseas funds in tourism development",
said Zhang Delin, Secretary of the Chongqing Municipality
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 30 million, Chongqing became China's
fourth municipality under the central government last March after
being separated from Sichuan Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
