<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Fluoridate Drinking Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will soon
start a project to have its water supplies fluoridated, the
health department said today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the department said the South African
government had decided to adhere to the fluoridation regulations
of the World Health Organization and other international bodies.
</P>
<P>
According to visiting American dental consultant Herschel
Horowitz, by regulating the fluoride content of drinking water,
oral decay could be reduced by about 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
Professor Flip Van Wyk of the Pretoria University's dentistry
faculty said the fluoride program would first be implemented in
large cities such as Durban, Pretoria, Johannesburg, Port
Elizabeth and Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project was expected to reach 40
percent of the country's population by 2000. In the end, it was
hoped that about 60 percent of the population would have access
to fluoridated water at a cost of about one Rand (one U.S. Dollar
equals 4.7 Rand) per person a year, Van Wyk said.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be difficult to provide this service to
people in remote rural areas because they did not have access to
a central water supply.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, he said, oral decay among these people was
usually lower than among urban populations who indulged in
western foods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
