<HEADLINE> U.S. Command Ship Calls at Hakodate Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Seventh Fleet flagship
Blue Ridge called at a civilian port in Hakodate on Japan's main
northern island of Hokkaido this morning, meeting protests by
local antimilitary groups, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. navy said the call by the 18,372-ton command ship, the
home port of which is Yokosuka, southwest of Tokyo, aims at
promoting friendship between the two countries, getting supplies
and giving crew members a rest.
</P>
<P>
But local antimilitary labor unions staged a protest rally
around the port, saying the visit is to help with a U.S. request
to allow its military to use the facility if a crisis arises
around Japan.
</P>
<P>
Hakodate is one of the civilian ports the United States hopes
to use in case of an emergency in areas around Japan under the
recently issued new guidelines for Japan-U.S. defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Before entering the port, the Blue Ridge and Japanese Maritime
Self-Defense Force destroyer Hamagiri had been jointly conducting
transmission and battle formation exercises.
</P>
<P>
The Blue Ridge visited a Tokyo civilian port last week,
following a series of U.S. military ship visits to Japanese ports
last month.
</P>
<P>
Five U.S. warships, including the command ship Coronado,
aircraft carrier Nimitz, called at Japanese ports last month in an
unprecedented move believed to prepare for use of such ports by
the U.S. military in case of emergencies in areas surrounding
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
