<HEADLINE> Maize Shortage Boosts Crop's Futures Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A shortage of nearly one
million tons of white maize in countries north of South Africa
and rising drought concerns have prompted conclusions of a record
2,500 futures transactions in September.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by the Business Day newspaper today which
said the transactions were worth 160 million Rand (34 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Maize futures traders reported increasing demand and
uncertainty due to shortages in countries further north of South
Africa and the impending El Nino phenomenon which traditionally
heralded drought in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The South Africa Futures Exchange (Safex) said Thursday that
in the third quarter of the year a total of 637,700 tons of maize
was traded, an eight-fold increase over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Prices for maize futures have risen steadily this year.
</P>
<P>
Safex said the price for the September 1997 white maize
contract was 770 Rand (about 165 US Dollars) per ton. It has
risen to 804 Rand (172 US Dollars) for December, 842 (180 US
Dollars) for March 1998 and 820 (176 dollars) for May.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, an estimated 400,000 to 600,000 tons of maize
was held back by farmers and cooperatives due to fear about the
El Nino effect and hopes of capitalization on rising prices.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, produced by warming of Pacific surface waters off
South America, seems to bite early this year.
</P>
<P>
There were speculations that this year's El Nino could be
worse than that in 1982-83, which caused damage of 13 billion
Dollars worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
