<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis Resumes in South Nigeria's Oil Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- An unspecific number of people were
feared dead while serveral others seriously injured in Thursday's
renewed hostilities between youths of two local rival communities in
Warri, an oil producing town in the southern Nigerian state of Delta.
</P>
<P>
Several houses and stores were razed during the feud between Ijaw
and Itsekiri ethnic groups which started around midnight and lasted
till 4:00 in the morning, the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sproradic exchange of gun fire was reported while the rampaging
youths went around burning houses and other structures at a market and
other places of the town.
</P>
<P>
Commercial and other economic activities were immediately paralyzed
as the Warri main market and other business outfits along the main
street were closed to prevent looting.
</P>
<P>
Oil and service companies also shelved the routine movement of
their workers and equipment to installations in the riverine areas or
fear of attacks from the rampaging youths.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, which broke the fragile peace in the town
in the past three months, the Warri task force beefed
up security by increasing the number of uniformed men at strategic
locations in the city to ward off the rioters and stem the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The clash between the two ethnic groups began in March this year
over the relocation of the headquarters of Warri Southwest Local
Government from Ogbe-Ijoh, an Ijaw settlement, to Ogidigben, owned by
the Itsekiris.
</P>
<P>
The federal government since drafted soldiers to Warri to restore
normalcy while the Delta state government instituted a tribunal to
look into the causes of the constant feud between the three major
ethnic groups, Urhobos, Ijaws and Itsekiris.
</P>
<P>
Some Itsekiri leaders boycotted the tribunal, which was supported
by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
As some of those that appeared before the tribunal accused it of
bias and the state government of causing the fighting, the federal
government promulgated a decree last month, giving it legal backing.
</P>
<P>
Beside Warri, where there was crisis over the relocation of
headquarters of a local government, similar brutal clashes have been
recorded between the Ife and Modakeke communities in Osun state, west
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Serious social problems have aroused the concern of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
In his national broadcast to mark the country's 37th independence
anniversay, Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha vowed to crack
down upon criminal activities to protect the life and property of both
Nigerians and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He however did not reveal concrete measures in this regard, simply
saying that "in keeping with the administration's policy to redress
grievances and to fine-tune policy implementation, steps are now being
taken to review specific issues that have raised genuine concerns."
</P>
</TEXT>
