<HEADLINE> HK to Hire Students for Voter-Registration Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government will
hire 30,000 students to work for the massive voter registration
drive in December for the territory's first legislative elections
after its return to its motherland, a major Hong Kong newspaper
said today.
</P>
<P>
Officials have begun to contact secondary schools and tertiary
colleges for help from their students, said Secretary for Home
Affairs David Lan Hong-chun of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), according to the English newspaper
Hong Kong Standard.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to hire 30,000 Form 5, Form 6 and tertiary college
students," the newspaper quoted Lan as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Under our timetable, the students will help us to do the voter
registration for one week in mid-December," Lan said.
</P>
<P>
Attending a reception for the first National Day after Hong
Kong's handover, Lan said officials expected to register about 1
million new voters within one week.
</P>
<P>
Of the estimated 4 million qualified voters, about 3 million
have been in the voters' register.
</P>
<P>
Lan said the HKSAR government would publish the first copy of
the register in mid-January next year in time for the legislative
election in May. The registration is expected to be completed in
December.
</P>
<P>
He said the students will go door to door at night from Monday
to Friday and all day on Saturday and Sunday during the
registration period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
