<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Drifts to Lower Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
today drifted to a lower close going into the New South Wales
(NSW) Labor Day long weekend.
</P>
<P>
Volume was low, with only 312.57 million shares traded worth
477.5 million US dollars, with some market players leaving for
holidays early, and others cautious ahead of key employment data
due out in the United States tonight.
</P>
<P>
A fall in the gold price further dampened sentiment in the
resources sector, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 15.8 points softer at 2,763.1
after the Dow Jones industrial average rose 12.03 points to
8,027.53 in New York overnight.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 14.4 points down at 1,365.8,
with bellwether BHP losing 17 cents, or 1.04 percent, to 16.18
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbrokings' Jamie Spiteri said the weaker gold price
contributed to general sentiment in the resources sector.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion in Sydney was trading at 331.75 US dollars an
ounce compared to 333.05 US dollars here last, while base metals
were mixed overnight.
</P>
<P>
Mining giant Rio Tinto shed 21 cents to 21.03 Australian
dollars and WMC lost seven to 6.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 29.7 points lower at 1,327.3.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 18.6 points weaker at
4,539.4, led lower by News Corp.
</P>
<P>
The media giant's ordinary shares sank 15 cents to 6.85
Australian dollars while its preferred shares lost 24 cents, or
3.91 percent, to 5.90 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, NAB fell 14.9 cents to 21.601 Australian
dollars, Westpac shed four to 8.54 Australian dollars and ANZ
added two to 11.41 Australian dollars. CBA gained 18 cents to
17.25 Australian dollars.  
</P>
