<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Enhance Electric Power Coop with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mozambique
and Malawi have signed a memorandum of understanding on putting
up a power transmission line between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed here on Thursday by John Kachamila,
the Mozambican Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources, and
Dumbo Lemani, Malawi's Minister of Energy and Mining, the
Noticias newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also sets a date for the signing and
implementing of an inter-governmental agreement by the two
governments and relevant enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the transmission line between Cabora
Bassa Dam in Mozambique and Malawi will cost 37 million U.S.
dollars. The project will make it possible for Malawi to import
energy from Mozambique and other signatories of the South
African Energy Network (SAPP). The two countries will also start
their joint fund-raising activities for the project.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Kachamila expressed the hope that
an agreement would be reached on power supply from Mozambique to
Malawi. He also hoped that the new transmission line will
benefit both Malawi and the north part of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The Malawi minister said his country is working hard to build
more hydro-power stations on River Chire, which could also
provide power to the Mozambican side of the common border.
</P>
<P>
According to him, electricity currently consumed in the
Mozambican provinces of Tete, Zambezia and Niassa comes from
Malawi.
</P>
<P>
The Malawi delegation also met Mozambican Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi. The delegatin will visit Songo, Tete province
today to see the Cabora Bassa hydro-power station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
