<HEADLINE> Australian Politician Attempts Suicide Over Allowance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia's leading opposition
party's deputy Senate leader Nick Sherry shocked the nation by
making suicide attempt last night over mistaken travel claims,
local media reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Sherry was recovering in hospital today from an apparent
suicide attempt after a week of political pressure over the
mistaken travel allowance claims, the Australian Associate Press
(AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Senator Sherry, Labor Party's deputy Senate leader, had
detailed his frustration over attacks on him in a hand-written
letter delivered to the AAP early today. The letter raised fears
for his safety which led to police breaking down the door of his
Canberra flat.
</P>
<P>
Inside they found Sherry, 41, covered in blood with his wrists
slashed, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Local television channel Ten Capital also confirmed the suicide
attempt by Sherry in its evening news today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government was plunged into a crisis as after
Prime Minister John Howard accepted the resignation of three
government ministers over the alleged claims and cover-up, and
sacked his senior political adviser late last month.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for opposition Leader Kim Beazley said Sherry had
remained conscious and doctors at Canberra Hospital expected him
to make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
Senator Sherry had been the target of a blistering government
tit-for-tat attack over alleged mistaken travel allowance claims,
centered on 230 US dollar-a-night claims for staying with his
mother at Opossum Bay, near Hobart, capital of the island state of
Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
In his note, written last night, Sherry did not believe the
political attacks on him would end.
</P>
<P>
"So I am taking the appropriate course of action," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard, who led the assault on Senator
Sherry, said he was shocked at the news and joined Beazley in
calling for privacy for Sherry's family and said he wished Sherry
a speedy recovery.
</P>
<P>
Senator Sherry, who was reported this morning to be
hospitalized last night suffering from "depression", is one of the
Labor's rising stars. He won the Senate deputy leadership after
the Labor's 1996 election loss and became a key figure in the
new-look team under Beazley.
</P>
<P>
Former Administrative Services Minister David Jull and former
Transport Minister John Sharp also resigned on September 24 after
it was revealed that Sharp had secretly repaid almost 9,000
Australian dollars (6480 US dollars) in travel claims.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, Science Minister Peter McGauran resigned after
admitting to parliament Thursday he wrongfully claimed about 1,008
US dollars in travel allowances from 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
