<HEADLINE> Two Foreign Firms in Kenya Given Power Generating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
issued power generating licenses to two foreign companies as a
part of on-going liberalization of the country's energy sector,
according to a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Kenyan Energy Minister Kirugi M'Mukindia
presented the licenses Thursday to representatives of Iberafrica
and Westmoni Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The minister defended the two companies against claims that
they were irregularly awarded the tenders to put up private power
generating plants in the East African country.
</P>
<P>
The criteria used in awarding the two contracts has been a
bone of contention between the Kenyan government and the
International Monetary Fund who has argued that seven-year supply
period is too short and the unit cost is too high.
</P>
<P>
M'Mukindia disclosed that his ministry was negotiating with
two other international power generating companies for providing
an additional 139 megawatts (mw) to the national grid under similar
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the liberalization of electricity
generation is part of efforts by the Kenyan government to
redress the current imbalance, leading to power rationing and
frequent black-outs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Iberafrica's plant in Nairobi and Westmoni's floating
diesel barge on Kipevu and Mombasa, currently contribute 88.5 MW to
the national grid.
</P>
<P>
The national peak demand for electricity is estimated at 744
MW while the current local supply capacity stands at 661 MW.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has drawn a five-year power development program which
aims at providing 338 MW in additional electricity power
generation capacity by the year of 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
