<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to React If Russia-NATO Charter Contradicted: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
today that Russia will react if the newly signed Founding Act on
Russia-NATO relations is contradicted by NATO policy.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French television FR3, Yeltsin
suggested the building of a greater Europe fully embracing Russia
but without the interference of "an uncle coming from outside."
</P>
<P>
"If NATO conducts a policy which contradicts with the terms of
the Founding Act, we will react," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is due to attend the summit of European heads of state
and government, which will be held on October 9-10 in Strasbourg,
France.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the first meeting of the Permanent Russia-NATO Council
held on September 26 in New York, since the signing of the
Russia-NATO Charter, or Founding Act, on bilateral relations in May
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He said that the New York meeting had allowed both sides to
discuss many issues and had yielded results.
</P>
<P>
"That gives the reasons to hope that the process (of NATO
expansion) will go ahead in a constructive way. At the same time we
want that NATO transforms itself into a political organization, into
an organization in charge of peace... That will make it easy for
all," said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if NATO moves in the opposition direction, Russia
will consider organizing "another kind of bloc of the East,"
although Russia does not need it and is not interested in it right
now.
</P>
<P>
"In the contrary case, we should think again about another kind
of bloc of the East, but we don't need it and it does not interest
us," said the Russian president.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin praised France and Germany for adopting a "prudent"
attitude toward NATO eastward expansion, to which Moscow remains
firmly opposed in principle.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the Founding Act did not give Russia the
right to veto NATO decision, Russia has the right to supervise the
process of NATO expansion which was kicked off by the NATO Madrid
summit in July with the admission of Poland, Hungary and Czech
Republic by the Western military alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
