<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Urges Cabinet to Do More on Deregulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today urged his cabinet ministers to try their best on
economic deregulation and other economic restructuring efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Economic structural reform led by deregulation is one of the
most important assignments for this cabinet," Hashimoto was quoted
by a Kyodo News Agency report as saying this morning.
</P>
<P>
The entire cabinet, he told a meeting of the ministers, "needs
to exhaust efforts to bring forward the timing of implementations
(of existing related plans) and add new measures."
</P>
<P>
Koji Omi, director general of the Economic Planning Agency,
told the meeting that the government needs to push the structural
reforms further to boost the economic momentum.
</P>
<P>
It needs to take more deregulatory steps in six fields, such as
high-tech information and communications, the distribution and
financial industries, Omi reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Also at the cabinet meeting, International Trade and Industry
Minister Mitsuo Horiuchi warned that "the state of the (Japanese)
economy does not warrant any optimism."
</P>
<P>
The government should engineer an economic growth that is based
on domestic demands, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
