<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports Increase in July: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The slide in the value of the
baht helped spur year-on-year export growth of 24.2 percent in
July, with the current account showing a relatively stable level,
according to the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
After discounting the effects of the 16.3 percent depreciation
of the baht in July, the nominal increase of exports was 8.9
percent compared to those in the same period of last year, the
bank announced recently.
</P>
<P>
Exports were led by high-technology products such as vehicles
and parts, transformers, telecommunication products, electronic
circuits, plastics, chemicals and canned food.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months, exports grew by 6 percent compared
with those for the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports in July increased by 9.1 percent compared with the
same month of last year, with imported cars and luxury products
dropping by 24.1 percent and capital goods imports by 16.5
percent, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The July trade and current account deficits stood at 22 billion
baht (628 million U.S. dollars) and 20.5 billion baht (585 million
dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
"If this trend is sustained, the total current account deficit
for the year would be around 5.2 percent of gross domestic
product, or just slightly below, Kleothong Hetrakul, director of
the central bank's economic research department was quoted
Wednesday by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund has set a target for the
Thailand's current account deficit this year at 5 percent of GDP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
