<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for "Greater Europe without Uncle from Outside" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- In a clear reference to the United
States, Russian President Boris Yeltsin today called for the
building of a greater Europe without the interference of "an uncle
coming from outside".
</P>
<P>
In an interview with French television channel FR3 and the
Russian television ORT on the eve of his trip to Strasbourg, France,
to attend a summit of European states next week, the Russian
president also suggested elaborating a "charter of European
security," an idea first put forward by France.
</P>
<P>
"Europe without Russia is not Europe. It is only with Russia
could it become a greater Europe, unequaled on the surface of the
earth," said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to define what is Europe which will enter in the
21st century, and it is in this goal that all the chiefs of state of
Europe have decided to meet in Strasbourg and express their point of
view," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president said that there is no reason to fear
"whichever country in this Europe embracing Russia," and called
on all Europeans to "unite in the greater Europe without division
line and find a common basis, a platform of union."
</P>
<P>
"We ourselves are capable of uniting ourselves in Europe
seriously and living normally so that our peoples live in security,
prosperity and peace. We don't need any uncle coming from
outside,''said the Russian president.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that all European countries put their ideas together
in a charter of European security, "whose objective is to create a
greater united Europe, a Europe without division lines."
</P>
<P>
France proposed the signing of a European security charter, which
does not have the binding power of a treaty, a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac proposed a privileged
European-Russia partnership when he visited Russia last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
