<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Balance of Payments Record Huge Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's balance of payments
in August recorded a larger deficit from 51.5 billion baht (1.4
billion U.S. dollars) a month earlier to 146.1 billion baht (4.17
billion dollars), according to a Bank of Thailand (BOT) spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly because of the continued lack of
capital inflow and corporate foreign loan repayments, Kleothong
Hetrakul, director of economic research at BOT was quoted by
Wednesday's local newspapers as saying.
</P>
<P>
She noted that since the baht floatation, foreign investors are
still reluctant to channel their money back to Thailand as they
have no confidence in the economic fundamentals, political
stability or the measures announced to handle economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, corporations that have borrowed from overseas have
rushed to repay these loans, for fear that the baht might fall
further against the U.S. dollar and consequently increase their
debt burden, she said.
</P>
<P>
Capital outflows in the first seven months were recorded at
352.5 billion baht (10.07 billion dollars), 127.2 billion baht
(3.6 billion dollars) of which was sent out of the country by
non-bank companies.
</P>
<P>
The outflows were in a more serious situation during July and
August, after the flotation, totaling 197.6 billion baht (5.6
billion dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
