<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Leaves for Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- First Secretary of Myanmar's
State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC) Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt left here today for Singapore to attend a joint
economic committee meeting between the two countries to promote
economic cooperation, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the Joint Ministerial Working Committee on
Promotion of Economic Cooperation, Trade and Investment was held
in Yangon, capital of Myanmar, in January last year, jointly
chaired by Khin Nyunt and Yeo Cheow Tong, Singapore Minister of
Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
During the first meeting, the two sides discussed cooperation
in hotel and agricultural sectors as well as cooperation
opportunities in human resources development. The two sides also
reached a new aviation accord amending the old one signed in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Singapore initiated an agreement on bilateral
economic cooperation during a visit to Singapore by Myanmar SLORC
Chairman Senior-General Than Shwe in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
In March 1994, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong visited
Myanmar, prompting a large volume of Singapore investment pouring
in the country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July this year, Singapore's investment in Myanmar
amounted to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in 56 projects covering
hotels and tourism, industrial zone and container terminals as
well as the industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's investment ranked the second after the United
Kingdom in Myanmar's 6.36-billion-dollar total foreign investment
from 22 countries and regions, according to official statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Inflation Rate Reaches 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Macao's inflation rate in the
first eight months of this year was 4 percent, latest statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, measured by the composite consumer price
index (CCPI), rose 4 percent between January and August this year
compared with the same period of last year, according to figures
released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The CCPI also increased 4 percent between August last year and
August this year, when compared with the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The price of foodstuff rose a little bit in August from July.
But the cost of transportation, durable goods, garment and
footwear dropped.
</P>
<P>
Macao's inflation rate stood at 4.8 percent for 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
