<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government Committed to Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has urged
the Kenya Tea Development Authority (KTDA) to give maximum
support to small-scale tea farmers to ensure increased
production, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Agriculture Minister Darius Mbela was quoted as saying
that small-scale farmers could increase their yields
significantly if they improved the use of fertilizer and adopt
better harvesting techniques.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking at the KTDA's annual growers
conference held here Thursday. He said that the government had
liberalized the tea sub-sector of small holders so as to give tea
growers powers to manage their affairs.
</P>
<P>
KTDA sold all its shares in small-holder tea factories to
farmers, and the 44 small-holder tea factories had their own
boards of directors to ensure greater control of the industry by
the producers, Mbela added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government also gave powers to the tea industry in
allowing it to manage tea cess for improving roads and the KTDA
has undertaken an expansion program for small-holder tea
factories.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the minister said, the program would enable
these factories to increase their annual processing capacity to
655 million kilograms from 555 million kilograms at present.
</P>
<P>
According to Mbela, tea production in the first half of this
year is 27 percent lower than in the same period of last year and
the production for 1997 is estimated to decline owing to
prolonged drought suffered late last year and early this year in
the tea-producing areas.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's share of the world tea market has increased from 5.5
percent to nearly 17 percent in the last 25 years and the tea
industry has become the country's leading foreign exchange
earner, accounting for 20 percent of Kenya's total export
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Kenya exports tea to more than 40 foreign countries including
the United Kingdom, Pakistan, Egypt, Ireland, Sudan and
Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
