<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 52 ADF Rebels Killed in W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 52 rebels of the
Allied Democratic Forces ( ADF) were killed in a mop-up operation
in western Uganda from Tuesday night to Wednesday, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Report from the scene of the battle said government troops
launched their operation at around 08:00 pm, and overran a
hideout in a deep forest in Bugoye sub-county, Kasese District.
</P>
<P>
The hideout, surrounded by a plantation of sugar cane, banana
and cassava, was used to be a source of water and food for the
ADF rebels, a field commander told The New Vision.
</P>
<P>
The hideout had been deserted when it was found by the
government troops. On Wednesday morning, ADF rebels fell into an
ambush when they returned.
</P>
<P>
The rebels escaped in a hurry, carrying away only the chopped
heads of their dead colleagues and leaving the bodies in the
field to avoid too much harassment, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Charles Angina, Operation Coordinator in west Uganda, put the
death toll of the government troops at two, and the civilian
victims at 29.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Ugandan army was reinforcing its
deployment in the west of the country. President Yoweri Museveni
has promised to put down ADF rebellion and said earlier that
3,000 additional soldiers would be deployed in the region.
</P>
<P>
ADF is a rebel group operating in west Uganda. It had some
1,500 fighters in its ranks up to last November, but now it
shrank to 450 members, according to a recent report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
