<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Satellite Switched Off, Likely Be Abandoned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- India's most advanced
communication satellite Insat-2d, which was launched on June 4 by
the French Ariane-4 rocket, was switched off indefinitely on
Thursday following a major power failure, the local press said
today.
</P>
<P>
Due to the power failure, the satellite lost its earth lock, a
mechanism that directs the satellite towards the earth, crippling
the normal functioning of on-board transponders of the satellite.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Indian Space Research Organization (ISRO) said
the satellite might have to be abandoned soon as it now depended
on only one out of the two power buses, and it would not be
possible to pull on for long that way.
</P>
<P>
This is likely to throw operations of India's national stock
exchange out of gear and upset expansion plans of telephone and
television networks, observers said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very serious problem," a senior ISRO official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Insat-1c launched in July 1988 had to be abandoned in
November 1989 due to a similar power failure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Process Cassava into Starch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will soon begin the
processing of cassava, staple food in the country, into starch
and other industrial produce, local daily The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
George Nape, a researcher on cassava in Uganda, was quoted as
saying that the move is aimed at adding value to the crop and
transform it into a cash crop.
</P>
<P>
He said that the processing technology is to be adopted
from Nigeria and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Cassava, a cheap source of carbohydrates for communities, has
been transformed to an industrial crop with a large range of
markets in Latin America and Nigeria, Nape noted.
</P>
<P>
Figures indicate that cassava production in 39 African
countries yields 150 million metric tons per year. Uganda's
annual output of cassava in recent years is about 3.98 million
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
