<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa to Push for More Seats at U.N. Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- African countries had agreed
that there is need for the United Nations Security Council to
allocate a minimum of two permanent seats to Africa, said Kenyan
Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister was quoted by today's East African
Standard as saying on Thursday that two seats of the U.N.
Security Council must be given to African countries, adding that
European countries were over-represented in the council.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival from New York where he attended the 52nd
Session of the U.N. General Assembly, Musyoka said Kenya
appreciated the role played by U.N. Secretary General Koffi Annan
in bringing about reforms at the global body.
</P>
<P>
The minister who also attended the U.N. Special Session on
Africa said that Annan's reforms package contains many positive
proposals and African countries will continue to push for a
complete reform of the U.N. systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
