<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Target for 1997-98 to Be Achieved: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Export Promotion
Bureau is to introduce non-traditional items in the world market
to meet the challenges in the export sector.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Hasinuddin Ahmed, Director General of the
Export Promotion Bureau, during a press conference Thursday in
Multan, southern part of Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has set the export target of 9.5
billion US dollars for the 1997-98 fiscal year. However, the
export sector has been facing tough challenges recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have been facing difficult targets to be achieved,
still we believe that we would be able to enhance our exports to
the tune of 9.5 billion dollars during the current year," Ahmed
was quoted by a local press report today as saying.
</P>
<P>
He believed that these targets could only be achieved if the
Export Promotion Bureau enhances its working by manifold with a
strategy to explore world market for Pakistan's non-traditional
export items.
</P>
<P>
According to Ahmed, the Export Promotion Bureau is planning to
hold around 60 seminars, exhibitions and workshops during this
fiscal year at home and abroad focusing on the need for
export-oriented studies with high vigor.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Pakistan has great potential to produce quality
products," he said, adding that "for the purpose of export we for
the first time adopted planned approach."  
</P>
</TEXT>
