<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Thai Military Leaders Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Fu Quanyou, Chief of General
Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), held talks
with Mongkon Ampornpisit, supreme commander of the Armed Forces of
Thailand, here this morning.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that both countries, as friendly and close
neighbors, would further promote the friendly and cooperative ties
between the defense departments and armed forces of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Fu said since the establishment of diplomatic relations, China
and Thailand have conducted fruitful exchanges and cooperation in
various fields.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate the 'one China' policy adopted by the Thai
governments under different premierships," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fu said he hoped both sides will continue to strengthen
contacts and further enhance mutually beneficial cooperation in
exchanges between military academies, and in personnel training,
army building and military technology, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fu noted that General Secretary Jiang Zemin of the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee made a solemn statement at
the recent 15th National Congress of the CPC that China will cut
its armed forces by another 500,000 in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the PLA is an army working for peace and
this strategic measure is certainly conducive to world peace and
regional stability, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Fu briefed Mongkon on China's foreign policy, domestic
situation and army building.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Mongkon thanked Fu for inviting him to visit
China.
</P>
<P>
Mongkon said that both countries share identical or similar
views on many issues and that he hoped the two countries and the
two armies will further their friendly relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Fu on Thailand's domestic situation and army
building.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the talks was Kui Fulin, deputy chief of
General Staff of the PLA.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Fu presided over a ceremony to welcome
Mongkon and accompanied him to review a PLA three-service honor
guard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
