<HEADLINE> Canada Recalls Its Ambassador From Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada has recalled its
ambassador to Israel to protest against the reportedly use of
forged Canadian passports by Israeli agents who tried to kill
Hamas member in Amman last week, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Canadian officials as saying that Canada has
taken a grave view of the matter after determining neither the
two attackers were Canadian nationals.
</P>
<P>
Israeli ambassador to Canada David Sussan was also summoned
by the Canadian Foreign Ministry on Thursday to explain the
case to the Canadian authority.
</P>
<P>
The two attackers holding the Canadian passports are being
held now by the Jordanian authority.
</P>
<P>
Hamas (The Islamic Resistance Movement) leader Khaled
Mashal was attacked by "two Canadian tourists" on September 25
in Amman and later admitted to a secure Jordanian military
hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The two attackers were arrested by the Jordanian police.
Initial investigations showed that they are not Canadian
nationals, but members of the Israeli security service "Mossad."
</P>
<P>
Following the incident in Amman, Izz-Edding Al-Qassam Brigades,
a military wing of Hamas, vowed to attack Israeli interests in
different parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli security service has also promised to investigate
this matter, saying anyone behind it would be punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
