<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Rises in NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Crime rate in New Zealand has
risen for the third year in a row, show figures released by the
Police today.
</P>
<P>
For the year ending June 30, the number of offenses increased
by 2.05 percent to over 526,000. On average, there were a violent
crime every two hours and six robberies and 10 burglaries for each
hour in the country.
</P>
<P>
But it is homicide which saw the highest rise of 38.6 percent
from 119 to 165. Among these cases, murders picked up from 51 to
74 with the remaining being manslaughter, attempted murders and
infanticides.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Commissioner Barry Matthews attributed the higher
homicide cases partly to the massacre in the central North Island
village of Raurimu, which claimed six lives, and to the laying
more manslaughter charges in relation to road smashes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
