<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Get Tough with Drunken Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Traffic authorities in
Gauteng, South Africa's biggest province, have said that they
would not show mercy for drunken drivers and road hogs.
</P>
<P>
Launching "Arrive Alive" campaign on Thursday, Paul Mashatile,
a senior official responsible for transport and public works in
the provincial government said, "The time for polite warnings is
over."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 10,000 people died on the roads in South Africa,
2,000 of them in Gauteng province.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures announced by Mashatile are the enforcement
of the new legal alcohol limit of 0.05 percent, down from the
previous limit of 0.08 percent; the acceptance of breathalyser
tests as evidence in court and the introduction of roadside
traffic courts.
</P>
<P>
The new limit means that in the past three drinks were
allowed before the legal limit was reached, now the taking of a
single drink could spell trouble.
</P>
<P>
According to traffic department sources, first offenders face
a three-month licence suspension together with fines and or jail
terms. Second-time offenders can have their licences suspended
for up to five years.
</P>
<P>
The "Arrive Alive" will focus on drunken driving this month,
on speeding next month and in December and January there will be
a crack-down on drunken driving, speeding and people driving
without seat belts.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Gauteng Province, the Western Cape Province,
Kwazulu Natal Province and Mpumalanga will also be involved in
the campaign, Mashatile noted.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is administratively divided into nine provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
