<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Fish Production Still Short of Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's fish production is
yet to meet the yearly demand although it has showed an upward
trend over the past years, a press report said today.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Fisheries Department, this South
Asian country is facing a shortfall of about 0.95 million tons of
fish a year against the minimum requirement of around 2.35 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
At present, the sources stated, the per capita fish production
of the country is estimated at 25 grams a day as against the
minimum requirement of 75 grams.
</P>
<P>
The country's fish production increased by about 60 percent in
the last eight years, rising from 847,000 tons in the 1989-90
fiscal year to 1.373 million tons in 1996-97 with an average
annual growth rate of 5-8 percent, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Output in 1996-97 was about 1.364 million tons, up 8 percent
from the previous fiscal year, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total output of 1996-97, about 1.07 million tons of
fish came from inland waters and the rest 0.294 million tons from
marine waters.
</P>
<P>
The sources attributed the country's fish production increase
to the application of modern technology.
</P>
<P>
But they pointed out that fish production has been badly
affected by the use of pesticides in crop production in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The country has about 4.05 million hectares of inland waters
and 0.28 million hectares of inland closed waterbodies and
brackish water shrimp farms in the coastal region, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's marine water in the Bay of Bangal is estimated at
48,365 square nautical miles (about 89,439 square kilometers) with
exclusive economic zone extending up to 200 nautical miles (about
370.60 kilometers) from the base line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
