<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Vice-President Opposed to Tribalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Tribal sentiments would
undermine peace the country has enjoyed for the past three decades,
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma has said.
</P>
<P>
At a Colloquium on Culture of Peace here on Thursday, Juma said
Tanzania is not happy with the proliferation of ethnic strife in the
sub-region because it could fragilize the peaceful
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
He decried the habit of some people of fanning tribal sentiments
or racism as a means to achieve political ends.
</P>
<P>
Juma warned that resposibility of safeguarding peace in the
country lay on every citizen and not the government alone, saying
it is imperative that the people be told to be wary of politicians
who mix racism or religion.
</P>
<P>
He called on political parties to nurse a culture of tolerance
with leaders setting practical examples to their supporters,
insisting that political opposition does not mean hostility, enmity
or quarrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
