<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Incorporate New Mining Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is expected to
incorporate a new mining law and get it passed by Parliament to
free the mining sector from bureaucratic red tape, the local
Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be tabled for its first reading during the
forthcoming session of the National Assembly, Patrick
Rutabanzibwa, Principal Secretary of the Ministry of Energy and
Mineral Resources, said in an interview with the Business Times.
</P>
<P>
Rutabanzibwa confirmed that centralization of licensing
functions will be included in regulations forming part of the
proposed act "because they are administrative issues".
</P>
<P>
The legal, regulatory and financial framework for the mineral
sector which was announced in May this year by Abdallah Kigoda,
Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources, will also be taken care
of under the act.
</P>
<P>
A draft of Tanzania's mining policy which was worked out by
the Dar es Salaam-based Economic and Social Research Foundation
is awaiting cabinet approval.
</P>
<P>
Both the proposed mining act and the mining policy are eagerly
awaited to reinvigorate the mineral sector which has been on the
decline since the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
