<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 15 armed members of the
Kayin National Union (KNU) attacked a village in Myanmar's Kayin
State Thursday, killing six persons and wounding three others,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The group of KNU's 16th Battalion, led by War Nay Phu, raided
Mi Ka Thit Village housing a break-away faction of the KNU led by
U Saw Tha Mu He, who traded their arms for peace with the
government in February.
</P>
<P>
Among the six killed, most are U Saw Tha Mu He's family members
including a one-month baby, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
While attacking the village, the KNU used heavy weapons to
onslaught the government outpost in the vicinity as well, they
added.
</P>
<P>
KNU, the largest remaining ethnic armed group out of 16 in
Myanmar, has not made peace with the government although four
rounds of peace talks have been held. The other 15 have reconciled
with the government.  
</P>
