<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Tumble After Weeks of Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices tumbled
this week, ending four strong weeks of growth, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Wool International eastern market indicator fell
23 cents to 699 Australian cents (503 U.S. cents) a kilogram at
the close of the week's sales.
</P>
<P>
"The change in the composition of offerings from the superfine
selection of the previous week to a more normal selection of wool,
representative of the clip as a whole which is typically found in
Sydney and Melbourne sales, was the principal factor responsible
for the downward movement in prices," the Australian Council of
Wool Exporters said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers Dalgety expected prices to stabilize in a month's
time despite the weak outlook caused by less stylish and cheaper
wool dominating the bales on offer.
</P>
<P>
"Next week this scenario will remain, adding further downward
pressure to prices," Wesfarmers Dalgety said in its Wool Weekly
bulletin.
</P>
<P>
"However, weakness is only expected in the immediate term with
tabilization likely beyond this."
</P>
<P>
Sales continue next week in Sydney, Adelaide and Fremantle with
about 97,800 bales rostered for auction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
