<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary to Visit China for Long-Term Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley is leaving here for China Friday on a visit designed
to forge a long-term cooperative commercial relationship with
China.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Daley told a press conference that his visit
"should send a message that the United States is committed to
being involved and also being active in the Chinese market for the
long term, not the short term."
</P>
<P>
He and Chinese Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Minister
Wu Yi will co-chair in Beijing the 11th session of the U.S.-China
Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade (JCCT) established in 1983.
</P>
<P>
"We are not here for quick access and big money deals but
rather for the tremendous long-term opportunities that exist in
the market that will bring about economic prosperity in China and
create jobs in the United States," said the secretary, whose trip
is timed about three weeks ahead of Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said his meetings with Chinese officials will also help set
the stage for the upcoming visit of President Jiang, scheduled for
late October.
</P>
<P>
The issues he is going to discuss with Chinese officials
include China's admission to the World Trade Organization (WTO),
bilateral trade and commercial law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States and China will continue the
negotiations over China's full WTO membership, but he believed it
was not "proper" to set a deadline.
</P>
<P>
Before flying to Beijing next Tuesday, Secretary Daley will
make a stopover in Kong kong for meetings with Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa and American business executives.
</P>
<P>
He will also travel to China's northeastern city of Dalian to
open the first China U.S. Telecommunications Summit. The summit
was designed to explore business opportunities for American
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
