<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Okays Loan for Bangladesh Railway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has approved a 110-million-U.S.-dollar loan for a railway project
linking Bangladesh's less developed northwestern region with its
more developed east, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
At present, cargo and passengers must be taken by ferry from a
train line on one side of the Jamuna River to another line on the
other side, creating a severe bottleneck.
</P>
<P>
The railway project includes the building of a bridge and the
addition of a dual-gauge track along the lines so that trains can
travel the 99 kilometers without interruption.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to generate a substantial volume of new
freight traffic, including the products of the coal and hard rock
mines in the region.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the project will also help streamline Bangladesh
Railway, the executive agency, to make it more efficient.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 269 million
dollars, of which 117.6 million dollars will be provided by the
Bangladesh government.
</P>
<P>
Of the remainder, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries will provide 15 million dollars, the Spanish government
11.4 million dollars and the French government 8 million dollars.
The Export Development Corp of Canada is expected to provide 7
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan, which is interest-free and carries a 1-percent
annual service charge, is repayable over 40 years, including a
10-year grace period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
