<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Zealand PM Tries to Reassert Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jim Bolger has signaled that more state assets could be privatized
in an effort to try to pump fresh life into his unpopular
government and thus reassert his leadership.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Auckland Chamber of Commerce Thursday,
Bolger raised the prospect of further privatization of health,
education and welfare services and reform of the government-owned
Accident Rehabilitation and Compensation Insurance Corporation,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
He told the business circle that he believed it was "springtime
again" in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking the question: are busy ministers the right
people to run property companies, airports, coal companies (and)
television companies and so on?" he said. "The answer is 'no'."
</P>
<P>
He said greater private sector and community participation is
necessary to deliver social policy today, be it in health,
education, welfare, accident compensation or employment support.
</P>
<P>
Bolger added that the economy and business confidence have
turned the corner and the government is in the midst of the most
extensive review of its activities since his National Party came
to power in 1990.
</P>
<P>
His speech is widely seen as a scene-setter for the next stage
of the government and an answer to his critics who are suggesting
that it is time for a change of leader.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 months since the coalition of the National Party
and New Zealand First was formed, the government has been beset
with troubles created internally, causing government popularity to
plunge.
</P>
<P>
A latest opinion poll showed that support rate for the
opposition Labor Party was over 50 percent, while that for the
National Party was 28 percent and that for New Zealand First only
1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bolger is now trying to revive the government's popularity by
delivering the message of stopping ructions and getting down to
business.
</P>
<P>
But Bolger's strategy is likely to put his party in conflict
with New Zealand First, which insists that strategic assets like
TVNZ are not for sale.
</P>
<P>
The Coalition Agreement listed TV1 as a strategic asset not to
be sold to private interests and TV2 will be retained in public
ownership, though private sector executives could manage it.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that if Bolger wants his plan to go ahead,
the Coalition Agreement needs to be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
Reports said business people had told Bolger to ditch New
Zealand First as coalition partner, which was blamed for almost
all the troubles within the government.
</P>
<P>
Bolger's speech also represents an effort to relaunch his prime
ministership. Bolger has been criticized by some national MPs who
think he lacks direction of leadership and have been talking about
a change of leader.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
