<HEADLINE> China's Aviation Industry to Cut Jobs by 150,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- State-owned Aviation Industries
of China (Avic) will lay off 150,000 surplus employees from their
present jobs and channel them to other jobs by the end of the
century, according to an Avic working conference last month.
</P>
<P>
The decision will affect about one-fifth of the workforce in
this sector, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Avic calls this a strategic measure to promote efficiency and
enable it to accomplish its goal for 2000.
</P>
<P>
This is an important measure for deepening the reform of State
industries.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, Avic will have no more than 500,000 people under its
administrative and key corporate arms by 2000.
</P>
<P>
A maximum of 200,000 workers will be required for aircraft
production.
</P>
<P>
In 2000, it is expected that 10 percent of its companies have
an average sales income of more than 500,000 yuan per employee; 30
percent more than 200,000 yuan; and half more than 100,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The people to be laid off from these positions will not be
left to their own devices," said Ren Wei, an Avic official.
</P>
<P>
It is expected they will be re-employed in other jobs created
in the sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the recent 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China, reform of state enterprises will be deepened. This
will include opening up state enterprises to public ownership in
diversified forms and finding other jobs for workers surplus to
requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
