<HEADLINE> Public Transport Enjoys Priority in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Public buses in Beijing are
running under preferential terms, easing the strings brought by an
increasing crowded traffic.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Beijing Daily, apart from designating a
special lane for the public buses on the Chang'an Street, one of
the busiest in the Chinese capital, efforts have been made to open
new routes and prolong the operation time.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the city has added a total of 2,215
kilometers of operating length for the public transport sector
since 1992, and 42 percent of the public buses have extended their
service time.
</P>
<P>
As a result, public bus routes have been extended to 197 of the
city's newly-built residential quarters and nine of the suburban
districts and counties.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the bus service closed at 11 p.m. in the city and
7 p.m. in the suburbs. Now, the time has been prolonged to 12
p.m. and 9 p.m. respectively.
</P>
<P>
The city has also added 18 special bus routes leading to 68
tourist attractions over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
To make the travel more enjoyable and comfortable, the city has
introduced air-conditioned and double-deck vehicles to the public
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
