<HEADLINE> Indonesia Reaffirms Efforts on Economy, Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
said the government is striving to overcome a monetary crisis as
well as forest fires that have sent a huge cloud of smoke across
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We are working as hard as we can to overcome the monetary
jolts ... We are working hard to overcome the ground and forest
fires and the smoke that is spreading everywhere," the president
told a youth organization in Malang, East Java, Thursday, reports
reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah has depreciated nearly 40 percent since
January, but its sharpest drop began in July when it came under
attack by speculators.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was trading at 3,450 to the U.S. dollar Thursday
compared with around 2,450 before the currency came under attack
in July.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jakarta share prices slipped 0.01 percent Thursday
amid lackluster trading hampered by concerns about the weak rupiah
and tightening liquidity.
</P>
<P>
The government was forced last month to either postpone or
review 156 government and state-related projects worth 38 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, fires continue to raze Indonesian forests
although rain has reportedly begun to fall in some parts of North
Sumatra and East Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 hectares of land and forests in Sumatra and
Kalimantan were estimated to have been scorched by fires in the
last three months.
</P>
<P>
The haze caused by the fires has brought 20 million people in
danger of respiratory problems in the country as well as in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have offered assistance to Indonesia in fighting
the haze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
