<HEADLINE> S. Korea Sees HK as Base to Expand Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korean businessmen
regard Hong Kong as a base to expand their markets in China's
inland areas and Southeast Asia, a senior South Korean diplomat
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is now the fourth trading partner of South Korea and
the bilateral trade volume has been enjoying a growth of 10 to 15
percent annually in recent years, said Park Yang Chung, South
Korea's consul general to the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China, in a message to mark his country's national
day.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between South Korea and Hong Kong reached 12
billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a gateway to markets in China's inland areas and
Southeast Asia and it is also a trade and financial center in the
Asia-Pacific region, Park said. He believed that the trade
relations between Hong Kong and South Korea will become
increasingly closer.
</P>
<P>
There are about 700 South Korean firms in Hong Kong and they
have been operated normally after Hong Kong's return to China on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, all the businessmen in Hong Kong are
optimistic about Hong Kong's future, Park said.  
</P>
