<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- U.S. Dollar deposits in Uruguayan banks resumed
an upward trend in August with a total deposit of 7.2 billion
dollars, 60 million dollars more than in July.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, time deposits in Uruguayan peso rose to 5.449
billion pesos (about 573 million dollars), an increase of 134
million pesos over July.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua's revenue reached a record high of 306
million cordobas (about 31 million U.S. dollars) in its 1996-97
fiscal year which ended on September 30, an increase of 28 percent
over the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Byron Jerez, director of the General Revenue Direction of
Nicaragua, said that the country will continue fighting against
tax evasion "with all the force and all the weight of law."
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican cattle exports maintained a rising trend
in the first half of this year with the export of 298,065 calves
and 3,704 heifers, 97,381 heads more over same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The U.S. Albrook Air Base in Panama was returned
to Panama on Wednesday in accordance with the Torrijos-Carter
treaties.
</P>
<P>
U.S. assets in Panama include the Howard Air base valued at
1.187 billion U.S. dollars, followed by Albrook at 393.8 million
dollars, Clayton at 302 million dollars, and Rodman at 169 million
dollars. Howard, Clayton and Rodman will be reverted to Panama in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The total value of the U.S. bases in Panama to be reverted,
including land and installations, has been assessed by Panamanian
and U.S. consultants at 4.611 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
