<HEADLINE> Thailand, Mauritius sign business pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, 0ctober 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has signed here an
agreement with Mauritius to avoid double taxation and kick-start
investment between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The document, signed on Wednesday, is expected to come into
force on January 1 for Thailand and July 1 for Mauritius, the
local newspaper the Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there is no cross investment between the two
countries. But Thai Deputy Foreign Minister Pitak Intrawithayanunt
said after signing the pact that the agreement would encourage
Thai investment in Mauritius' marine products.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Thailand recorded a trade surplus with Mauritius
worth 473 million baht (18.9 million U.S. dollars) out of a total
trade volume of 563.5 million baht (22.5 million dollars).)
</P>
<P>
The country imported fish from Mauritius while exporting to it
rice, cotton and textiles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
