<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Recalls Ambassador to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said
today it has recalled its ambassador to Israel to protest the use
of forged Canadian passports by two suspected Israeli agents.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy made the announcement
while attending meetings in New York.
</P>
<P>
He said that Canada has nothing to do with an apparent attempt
to kill an Islamic leader in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Khaled Meshal, political chief of the militant Islamic group
Hamas, was assaulted outside his office in Amman, Jordan, last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two attackers have been arrested and are reported to be
carrying Canadian passports. In fact, they are said to be agents
of Israel's secret service Mossad.
</P>
<P>
Canada takes "great exception to the use of reputation of
Canadian passports for those kinds of purposes, and we are
recalling our ambassador to Israel back to Ottawa for
consultations on the matter," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
In diplomatic terms, recalling an ambassador is a way to
express sharp displeasure with another country, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
David Kilgour, Canadian secretary of state for Latin American
and African affairs, told the House of Commons here today that "it
can be confirmed that the two passports were forgeries."
</P>
<P>
Israel's ambassador to Canada has been summoned to answer
questions about the passport incident, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident apparently broke a tacit agreement between
Canada and Israel that the latter would bar its secret service
from using Canadian passports after they were caught doing so in
1981.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said that
it would be totally unacceptable for any foreign spies to use
Canadian passports.
</P>
<P>
There are fears here that the passport incident might lead to
reprisals against Canadians in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0203 </DOCNO>
