<HEADLINE> Committee Set up to Review Soccer Problems in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A seven-member committee was set
up today "to review problems facing football" in Sierra Leone,
where economic embargo has added difficulties to the people's
daily life.
</P>
<P>
According to the west African country's state radio, the
committee is to report back to Umaru Deen Sesay, the secretary of
state for sport of the country, in two weeks time.
</P>
<P>
The committee was elected after a meeting in which Sesay
addressed first and second divisions clubs officials on the
continued decline of the game in the country.
</P>
<P>
It will identify causes regarding the continued decline and
poor turnout of spectators at matches.
</P>
<P>
The country has been suffering an economic embargo imposed by
its west African neighbors to force the military junta to hand
over to the legitimate government it ousted in a coup on May 25
this year.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports of short supply of food items,
medicines and other daily necessities in Sierra Leone as a result
of the embargo, which was enforced in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
