<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, October 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen Thursday
announced a decision to let the Army to fire a laser beam at an
Air Force satellite, the first test of its kind that critics see
as a step toward a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department spokesman Michael Doubleday said the test
will be conducted within a few days. The Army will aim a beam at a
small Air Force weather satellite 640 miles (1,075 km) in space
from the Mid-Infra-Red Advanced Chemical Laser, dubbed the MIRACL,
at White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico.
(US-Laser-Satellite-Test)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Palestinian permanent representative to the Arab
League Mohamed Sobeih has expressed hope that the release of
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder of Hamas, would lead to the release
of all the Palestinian detainees in Israel.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Middle East News Agency
(MENA) Thursday, Sobeih said that Israel must set free all the
Palestinians it detained, which was an indivisible part of the
peace process between the two sides. (Palestinian-Israel-Yassin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A key U.S. official has acknowledged
international criticisms of U.S. sanctions policies and said
Washington needs to make them "part of a coherent strategy"
including seeking multilateral support.
</P>
<P>
"We... find value in many of them (international criticisms)
and will factor them into our future work," Undersecretary of
State Stuart Eizenstat said in a speech last Friday to the Global
Business Forum, which was made available Thursday. (US-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of Congo
has called for a United Nations Security Council meeting to
discuss the conflict in Brazzaville, capital of neighboring Congo,
according to Radio Cameroun here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Bizima Karaha, foreign minister of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Wednesday in a speech to the UN
General Assembly, the radio said. (Cameroun-Congo conflict)
</P>
</TEXT>
