<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Fire Laser Against Satellite in Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen today announced a decision to let the Army to fire a
laser beam at an Air Force satellite, the first test of its kind
that critics see as a step toward a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department spokesman Michael Doubleday said the test
will be conducted within a few days. The Army will aim a beam at a
small Air Force weather satellite 640 miles (1,075 km) in space
from the Mid-Infra-Red Advanced Chemical Laser, dubbed the MIRACL,
at White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the test is to collect data for computer models
used to develop ways to protect U.S. satellites against lasers,
Cohen, who is at a NATO meeting in Europe, said in a statement
issued by his Pentagon office.
</P>
<P>
Doubleday also said today that the test is fully consistent
with U.S. policy and violates no international laws. He defended
the test as a "logical step" in learning how to protect American
satellites against lasers that a hostile nation might one day use.
</P>
<P>
But no nation is known to have ever used a laser against a
satellite in space.
</P>
<P>
The 1967 Outer Space Treaty prohibits putting nuclear weapons
in space and the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty bans the kinds
antimissile defenses in space that former President Reagan's "Star
Wars" idea envisioned in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In 1985 the U.S. Congress explicitly prohibited the laser test,
but the ban was allowed to expire two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military has long wanted the capability to disable or
degrade satellites in space to deter other nations from seeking
such a weapon for use against U.S. satellites.
</P>
<P>
However, critics argue that once the United States develops the
capability, or even conducts live tests such as the one Cohen has
approved, a dangerous new arms competition will be created as
other nations do the same.
</P>
<P>
John Steinbruner, a senior analyst at the Brookings
Institution, said the test approved by Cohen signals the world
that the United States is ready to "start the game of destruction
and to legitimize it."
</P>
<P>
Steinbruner called the Pentagon's decision "an unbelievably
foolish judgment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971003.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Denies Deal with Israel on Yassin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today denied it has a deal
with Israel on the release of the spiritual leader of Hamas Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin in exchange for two alleged Israeli secret agents
arrested in Amman.
</P>
<P>
"There is no deal," King Hussein said after he and Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat visited the founder of
the radical Islamic Resistance Movement in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
The 61-year-old and ailing Yassin was set free Wednesday by
Israeli authorities on "humanitarian reasons." Sitting in a
wheelchair, he was then flown to Amman for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, an eloquent preacher, founded Hamas in December 1987
following the outbreak of the Palestinian uprising (Intifada). He
was arrested in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Having served eight years of a life imprisonment for his role
in the death of two Israeli soldiers, Yassin's release came after
two alleged Israeli agents in an assassination attempt against
another Hamas leader were brought under Jordanian police custody.
</P>
<P>
Two tourists carrying Canadian passports attacked Khalid
Mashiel, head of Hamas' political bureau, in front of his office
with a toxic injection on September 25. Mashiel was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Israel's intelligence service Mossad was accused of being
behind the murder attempt. Samir Mutawe, Jordan's state minister
for information, has said the suspected Israeli agents will face
trial like any other suspects.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said police are continuing search of their
accomplices. King Hussein said Tuesday that Jordan will never
allow anybody to turn the country into a site of acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Today Hussein told reporters that Yassin's release is hopefully
the beginning of more and similar moves.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he hoped Israel will free more Palestinians from
its prisons. He called on the United States to safeguard the peace
process by pressurizing Israel to fully implement its signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Yassin is reportedly to return to his followers in his homeland
Gaza soon after his treatment in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as a positive step taken by the Israeli government
in easing tensions accumulating since Israel's Jewish settlement
expansion in March and suicide Jerusalem bombings in July and
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
